{# ─── Chart 9 · The Half-Life (fiat purchasing power) ─────────────── #}
<section class="gallery-section" id="section-half-life" aria-labelledby="title-half-life">
    <div class="gallery-section-inner">
        <header class="gallery-section-header">
            <p class="gallery-section-eyebrow">&sect;III &middot; Historical Evidence &middot; Chart 9 of 10</p>
            <h2 id="title-half-life" class="gallery-section-title">The Half-Life of a Dollar</h2>
            <p class="gallery-section-subtitle">Purchasing power decay of $100 held in cash over 30 years &mdash; using the M2 monetary-base growth rate (~6.5%/yr) as the inflation proxy.</p>
        </header>

        <div class="gallery-chart-frame">
            <canvas id="galleryHalfLifeChart" aria-label="Fiat purchasing power decay over 30 years"></canvas>
            <div class="gallery-chart-fallback" aria-hidden="true">
                <p class="chart-loading">Loading the decay&hellip;</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gallery-section-prose">
            <p>The official CPI rate (~3.5%) understates the actual debasement of fiat. A more honest proxy is <em>M2 monetary-base growth</em> &mdash; how fast new dollars are created &mdash; which has averaged closer to <em>6.5% per year</em> across recent decades. At that rate, $100 held in cash today is worth $50 in purchasing power in roughly <em>eleven years</em>, and a quarter of its value in twenty-two.</p>
            <p>The chart is a clean exponential decay because the mechanism is. <em>Cash is not a stable store of value</em>; it is a slowly evaporating one. Every argument for holding bitcoin against equities applies more forcefully against cash &mdash; equities at least share in monetary expansion; cash <em>is</em> what's being expanded.</p>
        </div>

        <p class="gallery-section-source">More in this exploration &rarr; <a href="/the-half-life.html">The Half-Life of a Dollar</a></p>
    </div>
</section>


{# ═══ §IV · HORIZON ════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

{# ─── Chart 10 · CAGR Ranges Across Holding Horizons ─────────────── #}
<section class="gallery-section" id="section-horizon" aria-labelledby="title-horizon">
    <div class="gallery-section-inner">
        <header class="gallery-section-header">
            <p class="gallery-section-eyebrow">&sect;IV &middot; Horizon &middot; Chart 10 of 10</p>
            <h2 id="title-horizon" class="gallery-section-title">Volatility Is Not Risk &mdash; CAGR Ranges by Horizon</h2>
            <p class="gallery-section-subtitle">Rolling annualized returns (min, median, max) for bitcoin and the S&amp;P 500 across holding periods of 1&ndash;10 years &mdash; deliberately computed from 2015 onwards, setting aside pre-2015 bitcoin returns as unrepresentative of plausible forward outcomes.</p>
        </header>

        <div class="gallery-chart-frame">
            <canvas id="galleryHorizonChart" aria-label="CAGR ranges by holding horizon - bitcoin vs S&P 500"></canvas>
            <div class="gallery-chart-fallback" aria-hidden="true">
                <p class="chart-loading">Loading the distribution&hellip;</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gallery-section-prose">
            <p>At a one-year holding horizon, bitcoin's worst rolling return was deeply negative &mdash; the 'too volatile' objection in one bar. But <em>look what happens as the horizon lengthens.</em> Each bar collapses inward: the worst-case return rises, the best-case return falls, and the distribution narrows around a positive median. By a three-year horizon, bitcoin's worst historical rolling CAGR is already positive. By ten years, the bitcoin range collapses into a tight band entirely above the S&amp;P 500's.</p>
            <p><em>Volatility is not risk.</em> Volatility is the width of the short-term distribution. Risk is the probability of permanent loss of purchasing power. At horizons of five years or more, bitcoin's historical record shows the former but not the latter &mdash; the wide one-year bars compress into something the S&amp;P 500's never does: a wide median, narrow range, no negative tail. That's the entire argument for time as bitcoin's strongest ally.</p>
            <p class="prose-footnote"><em>On the data:</em> these stats are deliberately computed from January 2015 onwards, setting aside the parabolic 2013 run and the 2014 drawdown. Those years generated 1-year bitcoin returns above 4000% and below -75% that, while historically real, aren't representative of any plausible forward outcome. The 11 years that remain still cover three complete bitcoin cycles, and the same window is applied to the S&amp;P 500 for an apples-to-apples comparison &mdash; which means the chart's SP500 numbers reflect the unusually strong 2015&ndash;2026 stretch, not the long-run ~10% historical mean.</p>
        </div>

        <p class="gallery-section-source">More in this exploration &rarr; <a href="/the-bitcoin-horizon.html">The Bitcoin Horizon</a></p>
    </div>
</section>

